eliverance in Carme Riera's "Te de ix, amor, la mar com a penyora" -- tTeatro Viva!: Latino Performance and the Politics of AIDS in Los Angeles -- tNationalizing Sissies -- tIndex -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"¿Entiendes?" is literally translated as "Do you understand? Do you get it?" But those who do "get it" will also hear within this question a subtler meaning: "Are you queer? Are you one of us?" The issues of gay and lesbian identity represented by this question are explored for the first time in the context of Spanish and Hispanic literature in this groundbreaking anthology.Combining intimate knowledge of Spanish-speaking cultures with contemporary queer theory, these essays address texts that share both a common language and a concern with lesbian, gay, and bisexual identities. Using a variety of approaches, the contributors tease the homoerotic messages out of a wide range of works, from chronicles of colonization in the Caribbean to recent Puerto Rican writing, from the work of Cervantes to that of the most outrageous contemporary Latina performance artists. This volume offers a methodology for examining work by authors and artists whose sexuality is not so much open as "an open secret," respecting, for example, the biographical privacy of writers like Gabriela Mistral while responding to the voices that speak in their writing. Contributing to an archeology of queer discourses, ¿Entiendes? also includes important studies of terminology and encoded homosexuality in Argentine literature and Caribbean journalism of the late nineteenth century.Whether considering homosexual panic in the stories of Borges, performances by Latino AIDS activists in Los Angeles, queer lives in turn-of-the-century Havana and Buenos Aires, or the mapping of homosexual geographies of 1930s New York in Lorca's "Ode to Walt Whitman," ¿Entiendes? is certain to stir interest at the crossroads of sexual and national identities while proving to be an invaluable resource.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Jan 2021) 0aHomosexuality and literaturezLatin America. 0aHomosexuality and literaturezSpain. 0aHomosexuality in literature. 0aSpanish American literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aSpanish literaturexHistory and criticism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / LGBT Studies / Gay Studies.2bisacsh1 aOrtiz, Agnes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalave, Arnaldo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBergmann, Emilie L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEpps, Brad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalderston, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRomtin, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBergmann, Emilie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWalsh, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalessi, Jorge, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPiedm, Jose, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aQuiroga, Jose, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatta, Licia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUmpirre, Luz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGossy, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMontero, Oscar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Paul Julian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSilverman, Suzanne, econtributor.4ctb4https: